Q1. Count the total number of employees.
Answer
sql
Copy code
SELECT COUNT(*) AS TotalEmployees
FROM Employees;
2ï¸âƒ£ Using SUM()
Q2. Calculate the total salary of all employees.
Answer
sql
Copy code
SELECT SUM(salary) AS TotalSalary
FROM Employees;
3ï¸âƒ£ Using AVG()
Q3. Find the average salary of employees.
Answer
sql
Copy code
SELECT AVG(salary) AS AvgSalary
FROM Employees;
4ï¸âƒ£ Using MAX()
Q4. Find the highest salary among employees.
Answer
sql
Copy code
SELECT MAX(salary) AS HighestSalary
FROM Employees;
5ï¸âƒ£ Using MIN()
Q5. Find the lowest salary among employees.
Answer
sql
Copy code
SELECT MIN(salary) AS LowestSalary
FROM Employees;
6ï¸âƒ£ GROUP BY
Q6. Find total salary per department.
Answer
sql
Copy code
SELECT dept_id, SUM(salary) AS DeptTotalSalary
FROM Employees
GROUP BY dept_id;
7ï¸âƒ£ GROUP BY with COUNT
Q7. Count the number of employees in each department.
Answer
sql
Copy code
SELECT dept_id, COUNT(*) AS EmployeeCount
FROM Employees
GROUP BY dept_id;
8ï¸âƒ£ HAVING clause
Q8. Find departments with more than 5 employees.
Answer
sql
Copy code
SELECT dept_id, COUNT(*) AS EmployeeCount
FROM Employees
GROUP BY dept_id
HAVING COUNT(*) > 5;
9ï¸âƒ£ Combining AVG and GROUP BY
Q9. Find average salary per department where average salary > 50000.
Answer
sql
Copy code
SELECT dept_id, AVG(salary) AS AvgSalary
FROM Employees
GROUP BY dept_id
HAVING AVG(salary) > 50000;
ðŸ”Ÿ Using multiple aggregate functions
Q10. Display department id, total salary, average salary, and max salary per department.
Answer
sql
Copy code
SELECT dept_id,
       SUM(salary) AS TotalSalary,
       AVG(salary) AS AvgSalary,
       MAX(salary) AS MaxSalary
FROM Employees
GROUP BY dept_id;
